## Add Animations with Framer Motion to Next.js / React

### 1. Pre-flight checks
- Confirm this is a React 18+ or Next.js 13+ project.
- Check for any existing animation library (`react-spring`, `gsap`, `@react-spring/web`, `react-transition-group`). If found, ask the user if they want to replace it or use Framer Motion alongside it.
- Note: In Next.js App Router, Framer Motion components must be used inside Client Components (`'use client'`). The `motion.*` components themselves are client-only.

### 2. Install Framer Motion
```bash
npm install framer-motion
```
- Framer Motion v11+ is the current major version. No separate type package needed ‚Äî types are bundled.
- Do NOT install `@types/framer-motion` ‚Äî it doesn't exist and types are included in the package.

### 3. Basic motion component usage
- The simplest way to animate any HTML element is to prefix it with `motion.`:
```tsx
'use client'
import { motion } from 'framer-motion'

export function FadeInCard() {
  return (
    <motion.div
      initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }}
      animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
      transition={{ duration: 0.4, ease: 'easeOut' }}
      className="p-4 bg-white rounded-lg shadow"
    >
      <p>This card fades in from below.</p>
    </motion.div>
  )
}
```
- `initial` ‚Äî the starting state (before the animation runs)
- `animate` ‚Äî the target state (where the animation ends)
- `transition` ‚Äî controls duration, easing, delay, spring config, etc.
- Every HTML tag has a `motion.*` equivalent: `motion.div`, `motion.button`, `motion.img`, `motion.span`, etc.

### 4. Variants for coordinated animations
- Use `variants` to coordinate parent-child animations (stagger children):
```tsx
'use client'
import { motion } from 'framer-motion'

const containerVariants = {
  hidden: { opacity: 0 },
  visible: {
    opacity: 1,
    transition: {
      staggerChildren: 0.1, // each child animates 0.1s after the previous
    },
  },
}

const itemVariants = {
  hidden: { opacity: 0, x: -20 },
  visible: { opacity: 1, x: 0 },
}

export function AnimatedList({ items }: { items: string[] }) {
  return (
    <motion.ul
      variants={containerVariants}
      initial="hidden"
      animate="visible"
    >
      {items.map((item, i) => (
        <motion.li key={i} variants={itemVariants}>
          {item}
        </motion.li>
      ))}
    </motion.ul>
  )
}
```
- Children that use `variants` inherit the parent's `initial` and `animate` values automatically ‚Äî you don't need to repeat them.
- `staggerChildren` controls the delay between each child's animation start.

### 5. Page transitions in Next.js App Router
- Create a `components/page-transition.tsx` wrapper:
```tsx
'use client'
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'framer-motion'
import { usePathname } from 'next/navigation'
import type { ReactNode } from 'react'

export function PageTransition({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const pathname = usePathname()

  return (
    <AnimatePresence mode="wait">
      <motion.div
        key={pathname}
        initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 8 }}
        animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
        exit={{ opacity: 0, y: -8 }}
        transition={{ duration: 0.25, ease: 'easeInOut' }}
      >
        {children}
      </motion.div>
    </AnimatePresence>
  )
}
```
- Wrap the page content in `app/layout.tsx`:
```tsx
import { PageTransition } from '@/components/page-transition'

export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>
        <PageTransition>{children}</PageTransition>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
}
```
- `AnimatePresence` handles the exit animation when a component unmounts (e.g., on navigation).
- `mode="wait"` ensures the exit animation completes before the next page enters.
- The `key={pathname}` is critical ‚Äî it tells Framer Motion this is a new element when the route changes.

### 6. Scroll-triggered animations
- Use `whileInView` for elements that animate when they enter the viewport:
```tsx
'use client'
import { motion } from 'framer-motion'

export function ScrollSection({ title, body }: { title: string; body: string }) {
  return (
    <motion.section
      initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 40 }}
      whileInView={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
      viewport={{ once: true, margin: '-100px' }}
      transition={{ duration: 0.5, ease: 'easeOut' }}
    >
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      <p>{body}</p>
    </motion.section>
  )
}
```
- `viewport={{ once: true }}` ‚Äî animate only the first time the element enters the viewport (don't re-animate on scroll back).
- `viewport={{ margin: '-100px' }}` ‚Äî triggers the animation 100px before the element fully enters the viewport.

### 7. Gesture interactions (hover, tap)
```tsx
'use client'
import { motion } from 'framer-motion'

export function AnimatedButton({ children, onClick }: { children: React.ReactNode; onClick?: () => void }) {
  return (
    <motion.button
      onClick={onClick}
      whileHover={{ scale: 1.05 }}
      whileTap={{ scale: 0.97 }}
      transition={{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 400, damping: 17 }}
      className="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-md"
    >
      {children}
    </motion.button>
  )
}
```
- `whileHover` ‚Äî applies while the mouse hovers over the element.
- `whileTap` ‚Äî applies while the element is pressed.
- Spring transitions feel more natural for interactive elements than linear/ease transitions.

### 8. Layout animations (automatically animate between states)
```tsx
'use client'
import { motion, LayoutGroup } from 'framer-motion'
import { useState } from 'react'

export function ExpandableCard() {
  const [isExpanded, setIsExpanded] = useState(false)

  return (
    <motion.div
      layout
      onClick={() => setIsExpanded(!isExpanded)}
      style={{ overflow: 'hidden', cursor: 'pointer', padding: 16, background: '#f0f0f0', borderRadius: 8 }}
    >
      <motion.h3 layout>Click to expand</motion.h3>
      {isExpanded && (
        <motion.p
          initial={{ opacity: 0 }}
          animate={{ opacity: 1 }}
          exit={{ opacity: 0 }}
        >
          This content was hidden and is now revealed with a smooth layout transition.
        </motion.p>
      )}
    </motion.div>
  )
}
```
- `layout` prop tells Framer Motion to automatically animate size and position changes.
- No explicit `initial`/`animate` needed for layout changes ‚Äî Framer Motion detects the layout shift and animates it.

### 9. Respect user's motion preferences
- Always respect `prefers-reduced-motion` for accessibility:
```tsx
'use client'
import { motion, useReducedMotion } from 'framer-motion'

export function AccessibleAnimation({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const shouldReduceMotion = useReducedMotion()

  return (
    <motion.div
      initial={{ opacity: 0, y: shouldReduceMotion ? 0 : 20 }}
      animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
      transition={{ duration: shouldReduceMotion ? 0 : 0.4 }}
    >
      {children}
    </motion.div>
  )
}
```
- `useReducedMotion()` returns `true` if the user has enabled "Reduce Motion" in their OS settings.
- Always disable or reduce animations for users who have this preference.

### 10. Verify the setup
- Run `npm run dev`.
- Navigate to a page with a `motion.*` component ‚Äî it should animate on mount.
- Open DevTools ‚Üí Network and verify Framer Motion is loaded (look for `framer-motion` in the JS bundles).
- Test `whileHover` on a button ‚Äî it should scale on mouse-enter and reset on mouse-leave.
- Test `whileInView` by scrolling ‚Äî the element should animate in as it enters the viewport.
- Enable "Reduced Motion" in your OS settings (System Preferences ‚Üí Accessibility ‚Üí Display ‚Üí Reduce Motion on macOS) and verify animations are suppressed when using `useReducedMotion()`.

### Common errors & fixes
- **"You're importing a component that needs... 'use client'"** ‚Üí A `motion.*` component is used in a Server Component. Add `'use client'` to the file or extract the animated part into a separate Client Component.
- **Exit animations not working** ‚Üí Missing `AnimatePresence` wrapper around the component that unmounts. `AnimatePresence` is required for `exit` animations.
- **Page transitions not triggering** ‚Üí The `key` prop on the `motion.div` inside `AnimatePresence` is not changing between routes. Use `usePathname()` as the key.
- **`layout` animation causing jumps** ‚Üí Other elements are shifting due to the layout change. Wrap the group with `<LayoutGroup>` to coordinate sibling layout animations.
- **Animations run twice in React 18 Strict Mode** ‚Üí React Strict Mode double-invokes effects in development. This is expected behavior ‚Äî animations run once in production.
- **TypeScript error on `motion.div` props** ‚Üí Ensure `framer-motion` is installed and up to date. The types are bundled ‚Äî no separate `@types` package is needed.
- **Performance issues with many animated elements** ‚Üí Use `will-change: transform` CSS on frequently animated elements, or use `transform` and `opacity` properties only (GPU-accelerated).

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT use `motion.*` components in Server Components ‚Äî they require `'use client'`. Create a wrapper Client Component if needed.
- Do NOT animate CSS properties like `width`, `height`, or `top`/`left` with raw values ‚Äî prefer `transform: scale()`, `translateX()`, and `translateY()` for GPU-accelerated animations.
- Do NOT forget `AnimatePresence` when you need exit animations ‚Äî Framer Motion cannot animate an element that has been removed from the DOM without it.
- Do NOT skip the `viewport={{ once: true }}` option on scroll animations ‚Äî without it, elements re-animate every time they scroll into view, which is distracting.
- Do NOT ignore `prefers-reduced-motion` ‚Äî some users get motion sickness from animations. Always use `useReducedMotion()` for significant animations.
- Do NOT use Framer Motion for simple CSS hover effects (color changes, underlines) ‚Äî use CSS transitions for these. Reserve Framer Motion for complex, coordinated, or physics-based animations.
- Do NOT animate layout-affecting CSS properties (`width`, `height`, `padding`, `margin`) with `animate` directly ‚Äî use the `layout` prop instead, which handles layout changes more efficiently.
